<br>
I guess I just don't understand where you are coming from.  I studied years of physics, chemistry, calculus, and engineering.  I still refer to class notes, text books, and when we encounter problems with our materials or when we need new ideas on the job.  I wrack my brain all the time for knowledge gained in my education.  In my field I know of very few people who can do the same job as someone with a degree, and they are people with 30+ years of experience, who have dedicated themselves to reading on their own time to learn theory as well as application.<br>
<br>
I imagine there are certain fields where a degree is not necessary for success, but even those are not careers where everything is learned on the job in one month.  In any job it takes lots of time to learn all the ins and outs and to become proficient and even expert.<br>
<br>
As for being &quot;fortunate&quot; enough to get an education....I am from a very poor family, and I quit high school at the age of fifteen.  I went back at the age of 16, studied hard, graduated salutatorian, and got scholarships.  I paid for all out of pocket expenses myself for undergraduate and graduate studies (worked 30-40 hours per week throughout college), and finished with a student loan debt greater than many people's mortgages.  <br>
<br>
People can do anything they are determined to do, no matter where they came from. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/udryfft.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dryfft</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Evoker</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/13/02 1:25:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1180.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: hahaha</span><hr size=1> Elauriel,<br>
<br>
Well, I thought that I did qualify my comments to be in regards to my profession.  I looked again, and I didn't really.  So, my comments were regarding my profession, and personal experience.<br>
<br>
Me being a software engineer, and working with other software engineers who have Business degrees, EE degrees, etc.  Please tell me how anyone with a Business degree fresh out of college is any more qualified than me.  Hell, how are they even equally qualified as me? <br>
<br>
I don't discount a college education at all.  I definitely encourage it.  However, I don't place any one person above another qualifications-wise, just because they do have a degree.<br>
<br>
I look at it the same way as a musician.  There are musicians with talent, and musicians without talent.  The one without talent can take all the lessons and personal coaching in the world, but they're never going to be on par with someone with talent.   And you can definitely tell those with, and those without (at least I can).   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/udryfft.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dryfft</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Evoker</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/13/02 1:29:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1180.topic&index=43>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: hahaha</span><hr size=1> You can replace 'talent' with 'aptitude' in my above analogy to musicians for any field.  And that's my humble opinion. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/utoxxthewizard.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Toxx The Wizard</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/17/02 2:08:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1180.topic&index=44>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Please go back to the first grade and learn how to read</span><hr size=1> Spelling mistakes don't piss me off. If they piss you off, I believe you need to remove your head from your ass and realize that we are all human. We are open to mistakes. When we don't know exactly how to spell something, would you rather hear. &quot;WTB that thing that has right click shick of ice&quot; OR a god damn spelling mistake?!<br>
