<br>
Your problem is that you equate education with meaningless repetition or inapplicable skills. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Education is training to a large degree.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> That's why lawyers and doctors have to study cases for years before they actually administer to clients. Knowledge is a foundation, and then there are things you do in college to build on knowledge and theory such as interning or assisting in research. Those extracurricular activities are pretty much expected of you. I don't know any lawyers today who didn't intern when they were studying law. It's almost similar in the sciences. You do lab experiments in all your classes, and eventually in your senior year, you may write your senior thesis on an original experiment you led or conducted. <br>
<br>
Here's another example. Someone who is a native speaker of French doesn't make a better teacher than someone who actually studied and trained to be a teacher. Does the French speaker know how to explain elements of grammar or draw on different teaching methods to help students? Not necessarily. But I can assure you the teacher does know a lot of techniques to help students as well as ways to use dozens of facts and exceptions to make a general principle easier to understand. Student teachers also have to clock in a required amount of time in the classroom before receiving their M.A., and this gives them the education to go out, do their job with a skill set, and learn more.<br>
